9. INTEGRATION REFERENCE IMPLEMENTATIONS
This section provides illustrative code examples demonstrating how client applications or internal services might interact with WDIP components, particularly the notification subsystem. These are simplified examples focusing on patterns.

9.1 Service Notification Examples
9.1.1 Email Notification Reference (Python Example)
Demonstrates how an internal service might trigger a standard email notification via the notification service (assuming an internal client library notification_service).

from datetime import datetime, timezone

# Assume notification_service is an initialized client library
# for the internal Notification Service API or message queue.

def send_integration_status_email(event_type, status, details, recipients=None):
    """
    Sends a standardized email notification regarding an integration event.
    Uses internal identifiers for standard cases where applicable.
    """
    # Determine recipient: Use provided list or default based on context
    if recipients is None:
        # Example: Default to central monitoring for general integration status
        # In a real system, this might resolve RecipientID::CENTRAL_CONTACT
        recipients = ["integration-monitoring@internal.example.com"]

    # Determine subject and body based on event type and status
    subject = f"WDIP Integration Event: {event_type} - Status: {status}"
    content = f"Timestamp: {datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()}\n" \
              f"Event Type: {event_type}\n" \
              f"Status: {status}\n\n" \
              f"Details:\n{details}"

    # Determine tool handle (implicitly 'email' in this function)
    # This corresponds to ToolHandle::EMAIL_STD
    tool_name = "send_email" # Resolved from ToolHandle::EMAIL_STD

    # Construct the payload. In a real system, might use NotificationMessage proto.
    # For demonstration, we use a dictionary representing the core tool call info.
    # Note: This is a simplified representation. The actual internal call
    # might involve more structured data or service-specific client methods.
    notification_payload = {
        # Represents the intent to call the tool
        "tool_invocation_request": {
            "tool_handle_or_name": tool_name,
            "parameters": {
                "To": recipients, # Parameter name matches internal spec
                "Subject": subject,
                "Body": content,  # Parameter name matches internal spec
                "ContentType": "text/plain"
            }
        },
        "metadata": {
            "source_system": "client_integration_module",
            "severity": "info" if status == "Success" else "warning",
        }
    }

    try:
        # Send the request to the notification service/subsystem
        result = notification_service.process_request(notification_payload) # Hypothetical method
        print(f"Notification request processed successfully. Ref ID: {result.get('reference_id')}")
        return True
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error processing notification request: {e}")
        return False

