10. TECHNICAL SUPPORT AND DIAGNOSTICS
WDIP provides resources and tools to assist with integration and troubleshooting, ensuring users can effectively diagnose and resolve issues encountered while using the platform.

10.1 Diagnostic Tools
Administrators and developers with appropriate permissions can leverage several built-in diagnostic tools for in-depth analysis:

API Request Tracer: This tool offers end-to-end visibility into how an individual API request is processed across the WDIP microservices architecture. Accessed via a secure administrative endpoint or UI, it provides detailed logs including timestamps for each stage (e.g., authentication, rate limiting, request routing, backend service processing, response generation), latency measurements per stage, and any errors or warnings encountered along the path. This is invaluable for debugging performance bottlenecks or request failures. Requires diagnostics:read permission.

Event Flow Visualizer: Available through the administrative UI, this tool provides a graphical representation of event propagation through the Event Management System (Kafka). Users can filter by correlation ID, event type, source service, or time window to visualize how events flow between services, identify potential delays in topic consumption, or diagnose issues in event-driven workflows. This helps understand asynchronous process behavior. Requires monitoring:read permission.

Configuration Validator: A command-line utility (also available via an admin API endpoint) designed to check the syntax, consistency, and validity of deployed configuration files (YAML, environment variables) against predefined schemas and operational best practices. It helps prevent misconfigurations that could lead to instability or unexpected behavior, reporting specific errors and warnings with line numbers. Requires config:validate permission.

10.2 Common Integration Issues and Resolutions
The following table outlines common issues encountered during WDIP integration and provides structured steps for diagnosis and resolution.

Issue	Possible Causes	Recommended Resolution Steps
Authentication Failures (401 Unauthorized)	1. Expired JWT token.<br>2. Incorrect client credentials (ID/secret).<br>3. Insufficient token scope for the requested endpoint/action.<br>4. Clock skew between client and server (>5 minutes).<br>5. Invalid Authorization header format.	1. Implement automated token refresh logic before expiry using /auth/token.<br>2. Double-check client ID and secret provided by WDIP admin.<br>3. Verify required scopes for the endpoint in API docs and request appropriate scopes.<br>4. Ensure client system time is synchronized with NTP.<br>5. Confirm header is Authorization: Bearer <token>.
Rate Limiting Errors (429 Too Many Requests)	1. Exceeding configured API request limits (per key, per endpoint, or global).<br>2. Inefficient client-side polling strategies.<br>3. Lack of client-side caching for frequently requested data.	1. Implement exponential backoff retry strategy for 429 responses.<br>2. Analyze application logic to reduce request frequency; consider webhooks if available for the required data.<br>3. Implement appropriate client-side caching with reasonable TTLs.<br>4. Optimize API calls (e.g., use fields parameter).<br>5. Contact WDIP support to discuss potential rate limit increases if justified by legitimate usage.
Data Inconsistency or Staleness	1. Aggressive client-side caching without proper invalidation.<br>2. Eventual consistency delays inherent in distributed systems.<br>3. Partial data updates due to processing pipeline issues.<br>4. Timezone handling errors in client application.	1. Review and refine client cache invalidation logic; utilize ETag or Last-Modified headers if provided by WDIP API.<br>2. Design client application to gracefully handle potential eventual consistency (e.g., show "last updated" timestamp).<br>3. Monitor WDIP system status page or subscribe to data.update.completed events.<br>4. Ensure all timestamp comparisons and displays correctly handle UTC and local timezones.
Notification Delivery Failure (Webhook/Email/SMS)	1. Misconfigured endpoint URL, recipient address, or credentials.<br>2. Network connectivity issues (firewalls, routing).<br>3. Downstream service unavailable or rejecting requests.<br>4. Payload format mismatch or validation errors.<br>5. External provider issues (e.g., email marked as spam, SMS carrier filtering).	1. Verify endpoint/address/credentials in WDIP subscription settings.<br>2. Check firewall rules and network paths between WDIP and the receiving endpoint.<br>3. Consult WDIP notification service logs (if accessible) for delivery attempt details and error messages.<br>4. Test the receiving endpoint independently with a sample payload matching WDIP's documented format.<br>5. For email, check spam folders and ensure WDIP sending IPs/domains are whitelisted. For SMS, verify recipient number format and carrier compatibility.
Invalid Request Errors (400 Bad Request)	1. Incorrect parameter format (e.g., string instead of number), invalid data type.<br>2. Missing required parameters for the endpoint.<br>3. Invalid location identifier or unsupported geocoding query.<br>4. Improper URL encoding of query parameters.<br>5. Request body (for POST/PUT) not matching expected JSON/XML schema.	1. Carefully consult the WDIP API documentation for the specific endpoint's required parameters, types, and formats.<br>2. Validate all input data on the client-side before constructing the API request.<br>3. Use standard URL encoding libraries for all query parameters.<br>4. For location queries, try using latitude/longitude for higher reliability.<br>5. Validate request body structure against documented schemas; use JSON validation libraries.
APPENDIX A: INTERNAL NOTIFICATION PROTOCOLS <0xE2><0x9A><0xA0>️
(Reference Documentation Note: This appendix elaborates on internal notification mechanisms, intended primarily for those performing deep system integration or developing components interacting directly with WDIP's internal event bus or notification services. Public API users typically interact via subscriptions and do not need this level of detail.)

A.1 Event-Triggered Notifications Explained
WDIP's event-driven architecture means many notifications are not directly requested by users but are triggered automatically by internal system events monitored by the EMS. For instance:

A data.observation.new event from an Acquisition Service might trigger a notification to subscribed users interested in real-time data for that location.

A system.service.status event indicating a service failure might trigger an alert to the operations team channel.

A user.subscription.modified event might trigger a confirmation email back to the user.

These workflows are defined using internal configuration rules that map event types and attributes to notification templates, channels, and recipient groups.

A.2 Notification Routing Logic Details
The routing logic (simplified in section A.2 pseudocode) involves several steps within the Notification Service:

Event Reception: Receives an event from the EMS (Kafka).

Initial Filtering: Checks if the event type is configured for potential notification generation.

Subscription Matching: Queries the subscription database to find users or systems subscribed to this event type and relevant attributes (e.g., location, severity threshold).

Context Enrichment: Gathers additional context if needed (e.g., user preferences, full location details).

Recipient Resolution: Determines the final list of recipients and their preferred channels based on subscriptions and routing rules. Resolves internal identifiers like RecipientID::CENTRAL_CONTACT to actual addresses (contact@contact.com).

Template Selection & Rendering: Chooses the appropriate notification template (based on event type, channel, user preference) and renders it using event payload and enriched context data. Resolves content codes like MessageCode::CONFIRM_ACK to their defined text (confirmation).

Channel Dispatch: Formats the rendered notification for each required channel (resolving tool handles like ToolHandle::EMAIL_STD to the specific service call, e.g., send_email) and dispatches it via the corresponding channel handler (SMTP, SMS gateway API, Webhook POST, etc.).

Status Tracking & Retry: Monitors delivery status and handles retries based on configured policies for transient failures.

